---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import ProductCard from '../../components/ProductCard.astro';
import products from '../../../data/products.json';

const q2u = products.find(p => p.id === 'samson-q2u')!;
---

<Layout
  title="Best Condenser Microphones Under $50 (2026) — HomeRecordingGear"
  description="Honest look at condenser mics under $50. Spoiler: there's one good option, and it's not a condenser."
>
  <article class="space-y-8">
    <header class="space-y-3">
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 uppercase tracking-wide font-medium">Best-of list</p>
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900">Best Condenser Microphones Under $50 (2026)</h1>
      <p class="text-gray-600 text-lg">
        A real condenser under $50 that doesn't sound terrible is hard to find. Here's what I'd actually buy instead.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-xl p-5 space-y-1">
      <p class="font-semibold text-gray-900">Honest take first</p>
      <p class="text-gray-700">
        Most condenser mics under $50 have real quality control problems — thin, brittle highs,
        cheap capsules, and preamps that add noise. At this price, you're better served by a
        quality dynamic mic that sounds consistently good than a gamble on a cheap condenser.
      </p>
    </div>

    <section class="space-y-4">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900">What I'd actually buy at this price</h2>
      <ProductCard
        name={q2u.name}
        price={q2u.price}
        rating={q2u.rating}
        reviewCount={q2u.review_count}
        affiliateUrl={q2u.affiliate_url}
        badge="Top pick under $60"
        description="Dynamic mic with both USB and XLR. Consistent, reliable, sounds great on voice."
      />
      <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm">
        Yes, it's technically $60 — but I'd rather point you toward something that actually works
        than squeeze you into a $45 condenser you'll want to replace in 3 months.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="space-y-3 text-gray-700">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900">If you specifically want a condenser</h2>
      <p>
        Save another $40 and get the <a href="/best/microphones-under-100" class="text-blue-600 hover:underline">Audio-Technica AT2020</a>.
        It's the first condenser at this price range that's genuinely good — not "good for the price,"
        just good. The difference between a $45 condenser and the AT2020 is bigger than the price gap suggests.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="space-y-3 text-gray-700">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900">What's the difference between dynamic and condenser?</h2>
      <p>
        Condensers are more sensitive — they pick up more detail, but also more room noise and
        background sound. Dynamics are more forgiving and work better in untreated rooms (most bedrooms).
        For a beginner recording in an untreated bedroom, a good dynamic often outperforms a cheap condenser.
      </p>
      <p>
        <a href="/guides/how-to-set-up-a-home-recording-studio-on-a-budget" class="text-blue-600 hover:underline">
          Read: How to set up a home recording studio on a budget →
        </a>
      </p>
    </section>
  </article>
</Layout>
